<TITLE> European shares extend gains after US data </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares rose on Tuesday after data showed US wholesale inflation met expectations in March, while a gauge of regional manufacturing activity beat forecasts. The US government said its core producer price index (PPI), which excludes food and energy prices, rose 0.2 percent in March, compared with a 0.5 percent increase in February, and right in line with analysts' forecasts. A separate report showed manufacturing in New York state stabilised somewhat in early April after hitting a record low in March. The two reports lifted U.S. stock futures and helped the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares rise 0.6 percent to 1,283.15 points by 1236 GMT. The index was set for its first full-day rise since April 7. Repsol and BG Group were among the top three positive influences on the European market after the two companies, in partnership with Brazilian state oil company Petrobras, unveiled an offshore find that may be the world's largest discovery in 30 yea
